{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/2012/10/24/projections-projections-projections/","webpackCompilationHash":"dfd26dbe3cbb7e082b48","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Create a map of the earth isn't an easy problem. Projections basically tries to solve the problem of how to 3D element on a 2D surface.</p>\n<p>Tons of papers have been written about this problem but a nice place to start is the wikipedia entry about <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Map_projection\">Map Projections</a>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 395px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 42.53164556962025%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Cylindrical projection\" title=\"Cylindrical projection\" src=\"/static/77b52223c4ca0689ed8d51a78ae6cd71/a4a4a/Usgs_map_miller_cylindrical.png\" srcset=\"/static/77b52223c4ca0689ed8d51a78ae6cd71/19bd1/Usgs_map_miller_cylindrical.png 163w,\n/static/77b52223c4ca0689ed8d51a78ae6cd71/d3bcb/Usgs_map_miller_cylindrical.png 325w,\n/static/77b52223c4ca0689ed8d51a78ae6cd71/a4a4a/Usgs_map_miller_cylindrical.png 395w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 395px) 100vw, 395px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span></p>\n<p>Some time ago I seen a awesome video from the project <a href=\"http://www.win.tue.nl/~vanwijk/myriahedral/\">Unfolding the Earth: Myriahedral Projections</a>. On it, the author divides the sphere into a myriahedron (a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron\">polyhedron</a> with a very large number of faces) which allows to unfold the sphere in many different map projections.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b1xXTi1nFCo\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 642px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 60.436137071651096%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Unfolding the Earth Myriahedral projections1\" title=\"Unfolding the Earth - Myriahedral projections\" src=\"/static/4195ef432b281e98e7bc86ab9e66602d/b582c/Unfolding-the-Earth-Myriahedral-projections1.png\" srcset=\"/static/4195ef432b281e98e7bc86ab9e66602d/19bd1/Unfolding-the-Earth-Myriahedral-projections1.png 163w,\n/static/4195ef432b281e98e7bc86ab9e66602d/d3bcb/Unfolding-the-Earth-Myriahedral-projections1.png 325w,\n/static/4195ef432b281e98e7bc86ab9e66602d/b582c/Unfolding-the-Earth-Myriahedral-projections1.png 642w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 642px) 100vw, 642px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span></a></p>\n<p>Recently I could seen another nice experiment at the <a href=\"http://bl.ocks.org/\">bl.ocks.org</a> site. The <a href=\"http://bl.ocks.org/3711652\">Projection Transitions</a> is an great map work example implemented with <a href=\"http://d3js.org/\">D3.js</a> library which shows an animated transition of map projections.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://bl.ocks.org/3711652\"><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 300px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 99.33333333333331%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Projection Transitions 300x298\" title=\"Projection Transitions\" src=\"/static/017a0dc4549f3fa309e4f84f24b3ea25/135ae/Projection-Transitions-300x298.png\" srcset=\"/static/017a0dc4549f3fa309e4f84f24b3ea25/19bd1/Projection-Transitions-300x298.png 163w,\n/static/017a0dc4549f3fa309e4f84f24b3ea25/135ae/Projection-Transitions-300x298.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span></a></p>\n<p>Don&apos;t you think D3 is becoming a great project? I think I need to get some time to spend on it.</p>","excerpt":"Create a map of the earth isn't an easy problem. Projections basically tries to solve the problem of how to 3D element on a 2D surface. Tons of papers have been written about this problem but a nice place to start is the wikipedia entry about Map Projections.","frontmatter":{"date":"24 October, 2012","title":"Projections, projections, projections"},"fields":{"slug":"/blog/2012/10/24/projections-projections-projections/","readingTime":{"text":"1 min read"}}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/blog/2012/10/24/projections-projections-projections/"}}}